***Hashing at the basic form, not very safe
echo -n "hello" | md5sum #-n flag tells Linux not to add a hidden newline character at the end of the word. If you forget -n,
                           you will be hashing "hello\n", which gives you a completely different scramble!
echo -n "hello" | sha256sum 
sha256sum t.txt #this is for hashing a file
-----------
Modern $ Real-world use cases
echo -n "hello" | openssl dgst -md5 #dgst - digest
echo -n "hello" | openssl dgst -sha256 #stronger
echo -n "hello" | openssl dgst -sha512 # strongest and modern
openssl dgst -sha256 game_patch.iso #to hash file
-----------
openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -salt -pbkdf2 -in secrets.txt -out secrets.enc 
enc -aes-256-cbc: Tells OpenSSL to use the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) with a 256-bit key in Cipher Block Chaining (CBC) mode. 
This is practically uncrackable by today's standards.
-salt: (Crucial) Tells OpenSSL to generate a random 8-byte salt and mix it in. This protects your file against dictionary attacks.
-pbkdf2: Stands for Password-Based Key Derivation Function 2. It enforces a modern, super-secure method of turning your typed
password into an encryption key by repeating the hashing process thousands of times. Always use this flag.
-in secrets.txt: The original, readable file you want to encrypt.
-out secrets.enc: The new, locked, scrambled file that will be created. out files doesn't always have to have a .enc file extension, it can be anything
------------
openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -d -pbkdf2 -in secrets.enc -out recovered_secrets.txt
-d: Tells OpenSSL to decrypt instead of encrypt.
-in secrets.enc: You feed it the scrambled file.
-out recovered_secrets.txt: The name of the clean, readable file you want to output.
----------
head -c 16 secrets.enc | xxd #too peek to see if a file is salted or not.
